One year ago, on June 17, 2021, more than 150 years after news of Lincoln‚Äôs Emancipation Proclamation made its way down to Galveston, TX, President Biden signed a law marking Juneteenth as a national holiday. 3/4

More than 2.5 years had passed since President Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation when Gen. Granger arrived, and June 19th has been celebrated annually since, going by several names: Freedom Day, Emancipation Day, and Juneteenth Independence Day. 2/4

On June 19, 1865, about two months after Confederate General Robert E. Lee surrendered, Gordon Granger, a Union General, arrived in Galveston, TX to inform enslaved African-Americans of their freedom and that the war had ended. üßµ
